summary: Over the years I have accumulated a rich experience and interest in the fields of education and scientific research, and developed managerial and technical skills. I am an ambitious person, hardworking, responsible, resourceful, stimulated by variety and challenges that allow me to make good use of my curiosity and creativity. What keeps me going and makes me work harder is knowing that through my work I can help others, that I can bring value into our society and into the lives of others.

projects: [{'title': 'Mouse models for Fragile X-associated Tremor/Ataxia Syndrome', 'date': {'start': {'month': 10, 'day': None, 'year': 2013}, 'end': {'month': None, 'day': None, 'year': None}}, 'description': 'The project I was working on was focused on Fragile X-associated Tremor/Ataxia Syndrome (FXTAS), a neurodegenerative disorder linked to the same FMR1 (Fragile X Mental Retardation 1) gene also affected in the Fragile X Syndrome. The aim of my work was phenotyping a mouse model for FXTAS, a dox-inducible transgenic mouse that expresses the transgene only in neurons, following Doxycycline administration. In order to phenotype this mouse model, I conducted several behavioral experiments, such as: open field, ladder rung, automated 3-chamber test for social behavior, elevated plus maze and Morris water maze. After the behavioral testing, material was collected for further histological and molecular investigations. The project comprised of two main groups: one cohort receiving dox for 8 weeks, and the second for 20 weeks. The project is ongoing, and we hope it will lead to a better understanding of the syndrome, and also to valuable scientific publications.  ', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Andreea S', 'last_name': 'Pop', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Adviseur Ontwikkeling/ Projectleider CCSA at Rijkswaterstaat'}]}, {'title': 'Fragile X Syndrome: Steps towards therapy', 'date': {'start': {'month': 12, 'day': None, 'year': 2008}, 'end': {'month': 4, 'day': None, 'year': 2013}}, 'description': 'In the last 4 years, as PhD research project, I investigated the histological and behavioral phenotype of a mouse model for the Fragile X Syndrome (FXS), the Fmr1 KO mouse, and the rescuing effect of several pharmaceutical compounds on these phenotypes.\nFragile X syndrome is known to be the most common single gene cause of autism and intellectual disability. Thus the individuals diagnosed with this syndrome suffer from intellectual disability, morphological features and autistic-like behavior. As human studies are more difficult to perform in depth, animal models offer a good alternative. The Fmr1 KO mouse also lacks the fragile X mental retardation protein (Fmrp), and reproduces some of the characteristics of FXS: macroorchidism, hyperactivity, cognitive impairments, epileptic seizures etc.\nMy research focused on the dendritic spine aspect in the hippocampus of these mice, as hippocampus plays a major role in memory and learning, aspects known to be impaired in FXS patients, and on social behavior of these mice. We found spine and behavioral alterations that we corrected by long-term administration of an mGluR5 antagonist, AFQ056/Mavoglurant.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Andreea S', 'last_name': 'Pop', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Adviseur Ontwikkeling/ Projectleider CCSA at Rijkswaterstaat'}]}]
